Ancient Egypts Gods were very understandable, they worshiped all they saw that created life as well as what they saw that assisted life, for example, the ancient Egyptians believed that Osiris (the God of the dead, God of fertility and God of resurrection) gave them the gift of barley one of their most important crops.
A large temple was built to honour Osiris at Abydo.

They would not only worship things they saw as life-giving but also life preserving, that led to them having some extraordinary Gods,  like the Crocodile (Sobek) they believed worshiping what can kill you would spare you should they encounter any Crocodiles, but more importantly they thought that Sobek could protect the Pharaoh from dark magic.
They dedicated half the Temple Kom Ombo In Aswan to the Crocodile lol

What we see through ancient Egypts Gods is how their understanding Improved, for example their most worshiped God, most powerful God, was Amun (the king of the Gods) but later they realised that the Sun had a huge Importance to mans survival, so they took Ra (the Sun God) and added It to Amun making the all-powerful God Amun-Ra.
A large and important temple was built at Thebes to honour Amun-Ra.

We then see, later on, the most well-known shift In ancient Egypts Gods when Tutankhamens father Akhenaten understood without the Sun life would not exist. So he abolished all other Gods replacing them all with the Aten (the Sun Disk) 
Actually, makes perfect sense to worship the Sun. 
Opposed as to some deity of deception, greed, corruption, murder and savagery.
